# ## United Kingdom

# RSEs by definition, work for others. Their role involves writing code that is used by others which is confirmed by our results. Only 5% of the participants mainly code for themselves, while 30% choose the answer (5- mostly other people). 
# 
# 
# Their collaboration can also take other forms. This is why we asked with whom the participants work with. Usually, they seems to be embedded in a stable group, 45% of them report to work with the same researchers and 15% with the same research group. Only a minority has a more flexible collaboration (48%).
# On the side of collaboration, we wanted to know if they were working within a Research Software Engineer group. It is the case half of them (49%), about the same as last year.
# 
# On average, the participants work on less than 4 projects (1 project 18%, 2 projects 23%, 3 projects 24%). On this projects, they are often working alone (32%).  
# 
# RSEs have programming skills that is not necessarily shared within their field. Therefore, they can train other researchers to develop some best practices or learn how to program more efficiently. They are not teaching directly to students but transferring skills is an important aspect of their job. In average, they do training twice a year. These trainings are more often done under the form of workshop than traditional teaching and often do it as Software/Data Carpentry workshop or local university Training. A type of training probably more adapted to teach computing skills.

